1

00:00:00.480  -->  00:00:07.980
A key factor in writing clean semantically rich h tim now is choosing the correct element to describe

2

00:00:07.980  -->  00:00:10.160
a particular bit of content.

3

00:00:10.170  -->  00:00:15.450
So for example in an earlier lesson we learned how to create a bullet list.

4

00:00:15.480  -->  00:00:21.420
But in this lesson we will learn that HTML offers many different list types and sometimes it's a bit

5

00:00:21.420  -->  00:00:25.880
tricky knowing which list type to use to describe your list content.

6

00:00:26.220  -->  00:00:32.250
However by the end of this lesson you will have a firm grasp of the three most common list types.

7

00:00:32.250  -->  00:00:34.050
So let's get started.

8

00:00:34.050  -->  00:00:39.030
We will begin with a list type that you've already seen in action from an earlier lesson.

9

00:00:39.030  -->  00:00:40.770
The Unordered list.

10

00:00:40.770  -->  00:00:45.930
We choose the unordered list when the ordering of the list items do not matter.

11

00:00:45.930  -->  00:00:51.270
This means by changing the order of the list items we're not changing the meaning of the list as a whole

12

00:00:51.270  -->  00:00:51.630
.

13

00:00:51.630  -->  00:00:59.520
So a good example of this would be a grocery list unordered list list item.

14

00:00:59.550  -->  00:01:03.060
Milk bread

15

00:01:05.540  -->  00:01:06.980
carrots.

16

00:01:07.050  -->  00:01:11.970
So if we save and refreshing the browser receive bulleted list and the key point here is that it doesn't

17

00:01:11.970  -->  00:01:14.400
matter if carrots came first.

18

00:01:14.430  -->  00:01:20.400
That doesn't change the inherent meaning of this grocery list to clearly illustrate this point.

19

00:01:20.400  -->  00:01:22.100
Let's look at something different.

20

00:01:22.170  -->  00:01:25.340
Let's look at an ordered list.

21

00:01:25.380  -->  00:01:29.120
So in the text editor will create a new list instead of UL.

22

00:01:29.160  -->  00:01:35.100
We use o l which stands for ordered list.

23

00:01:35.460  -->  00:01:44.630
It also accepts list item like elements as children and will create a list of our morning routine.

24

00:01:45.090  -->  00:01:49.740
So the first list item is wake up.

25

00:01:49.740  -->  00:02:01.110
Then brush teeth then shower then eat breakfast.

26

00:02:01.140  -->  00:02:08.490
If I save and refresh the browser we see that instead of a bulleted list we receive a numbered list

27

00:02:08.990  -->  00:02:12.900
and this is because the ordering matters with an ordered list.

28

00:02:12.990  -->  00:02:16.890
The ordering is changing the meaning of the list as a whole.

29

00:02:16.890  -->  00:02:23.130
So if I'm showing you my morning routine it matters that these items are in a specific order to remember

30

00:02:23.130  -->  00:02:24.480
with the unordered list.

31

00:02:24.480  -->  00:02:27.560
We said that it doesn't matter if Carrots was moved to the top.

32

00:02:27.570  -->  00:02:31.510
It's still the same grocery list but with our ordered list.

33

00:02:31.590  -->  00:02:32.380
What if I moved.

34

00:02:32.400  -->  00:02:39.450
Eat breakfast to sit before wake up all of a sudden this numbered list or this ordered list doesn't

35

00:02:39.450  -->  00:02:40.710
make any sense.

36

00:02:40.740  -->  00:02:43.750
How can you eat breakfast if you didn't first wake up.

37

00:02:44.010  -->  00:02:47.350
So let's go ahead and revert that back to the original order.

38

00:02:47.580  -->  00:02:52.240
And this was all just a long winded way of saying that if the ordering of your items doesn't matter

39

00:02:52.250  -->  00:02:52.280
.

40

00:02:52.290  -->  00:02:54.420
Use an unordered list.

41

00:02:54.550  -->  00:02:56.740
You will and if the ordering does matter.

42

00:02:56.760  -->  00:02:59.790
Use an oh well ordered list.

